<statement>
<p>Solve this system of equations using elimination.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}-{2}{y}=-{15}</m> </p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{3}{x}-{y}={0}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="8" /></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left({3},{9}\right)}</m></li></ul></p><p>We chose (for no special reason) to use the first equation to eliminate x from the second equation.</p>
<p>To eliminate we need the scaled version of equation one to have a coefficient of -3. So we scale by <m>\displaystyle-\frac{{3}}{{1}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-\frac{{{3}}}{{1}}{\left({1}{x}+-{2}{y}\right)}=-\frac{{{3}}}{{1}}{\left(-{15}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{\left({3}\right)}{x}+{6}{y}={45}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{3}{x}-{y}={0}</m></p>
<p>Adding these two equations gives us</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{5}{y}={45}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=\frac{{45}}{{5}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}={9}</m></p>
<p>Finally we can substitute this y value into the first equation to solve for x.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}+-{2}{\left({9}\right)}=-{15}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}+{\left(-{18}\right)}=-{15}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}=-{15}-{\left(-{18}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}={3}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=\frac{{3}}{{1}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}={3}</m></p>
<p>Thus the answer is <m>\displaystyle{\left({3},{9}\right)}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

